      <h1 class='title'>EXPIRY OF LEASES</h1>
    </div>
    <div class='grand-committee-report-sitting' id='content'>
      
      <cite class='section'>HL Deb 22 March 2001 vol 623 cc252-3GC</cite>
      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_252gc' title='Col. 252GC &mdash; HL Deb 22 March 2001 vol 623 c252GC' name='column_252gc' href='#column_252gc' rel='bookmark'>252GC</a>
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06413'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_91' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (" .&#x2014;(1) Schedule 4A of the 1967 Act (certain leases granted by housing associations) is amended as follows.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06414'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_92' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (2) In paragraph 3(1), after "a lease granted by a housing association" insert ", or which reverts to a housing association on expiry,".
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06415'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_93' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (3) In paragraph 3(2), omit paragraph (d).").
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06416'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_94' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        The noble Baroness said: The amendment refers to the previous Act and the low rent test. I highlighted the issue earlier. It is peculiar to registered social landlords and people who are in the process of buying their houses through shared ownership. This clause will ensure that shared ownership houses can be acquired only by shared owners, through the process of staircasing; that is, gradually increasing their interest in the property eventually to 100 per cent. As I understand it, originally there were amendments to the <a href="/acts/leasehold-reform-act-1967">Leasehold Reform Act 1967</a> and to Housing Act 1996 to deal with the discrepancies. Many believe that that did not do so effectively, with the result that now shared owners may currently acquire their freehold to their houses through enfranchisement from registered social landlords for very small sums of money. I am sure that this is not the Government's intention. I believe that the amendment would deal with it. I hope that Government will either say that that is not the case or that we can deal with the situation. I beg to move.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06417'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_95' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        4.45 p.m.
      </p>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0623P0-06418'>
        <a name='S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_96'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-andrew-mcintosh' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_96' title='Link to this speech by Mr Andrew McIntosh' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-andrew-mcintosh" title="Mr Andrew McIntosh">Lord McIntosh of Haringey</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I do not think that the amendment will deal with it, but the noble Baroness, Lady Maddock, has identified a real problem with the
            
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_253gc' title='Col. 253GC &mdash; HL Deb 22 March 2001 vol 623 c253GC' name='column_253gc' href='#column_253gc' rel='bookmark'>253GC</a>
            1967 Act. It was not designed with shared ownership in mind, and the best thing for us to do is to take the problem away for consideration.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0623P0-06419'>
        <a name='S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_97'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mrs-diana-maddock' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_97' title='Link to this speech by Mrs Diana Maddock' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mrs-diana-maddock" title="Mrs Diana Maddock">Baroness Maddock</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I am grateful. I hope that it can be sorted out this time. There have been attempts in the past and we have not succeeded yet. I look forward to a successful amendment in the future. I beg leave to withdraw the amendment.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06420'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_98' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        Amendment, by leave, withdrawn.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0623P0-06421'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0623P0_20010322_GCR_99' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <span class="member">Lord Kingsland</span> moved Amendment No. 235A:
        <q>After Clause 135, insert the following new clause&#x2014;</q>
        <q>(" In section 22 of the 1967 Act, insert&#x2014;</q>
      </p>
